title: For Sale:  Warning KSG shotgun 12 ga -   SCAM-  Read this before you buy
location: tennessee, oklahoma, kansas, texas, Oklahoma, United States
postcontent:
Check and double check if you are trying to buy a Kel-Tec KSG shotgun.  There are a lot of ads on ARMSLIST that are total SCAMS.
God's Blessing or email address   REDACTED is the latest scam artist.  Ask a lot of questions, serial number, phone number, address. Suggest going through FFL dealer only.  He refuses to supply any of the information, he's a scammer, thief, lazy SOB that steals.  Last time- through work with the ATF and police department, it was a guy in Nigeria.  US has no jurisdiction to arrest him. He has you send the money to a friend in the US.  
If the address changes to send payment to - it's a scam.
if the guy speak or types in broken english -- it's a scam.
if he wants a western union payment - it's a scam.
if he wants to sell a $1200.00 shotgun for less that $900.00 - it's a scam.
May cost you $20.00 by going through an FFL to do a transfer but could save you the whole cost, of a big mistake!  He refuses to use an FFL - it's a scam.

The established use of long laboratory test barrels that give false high velocity readings is essentially misleading to the public who won’t be firing ammo from a laboratory test barrel in the real world, where it matters.

    2145 fps - Marlin mod 1894, 18 inch barrel
    1583 fps - S&W mod 27, 5 inch barrel
    1591 fps - S&W Mt. Gun, 4 inch barrel
    1507 fps - S&W mod 66, 3 inch barrel
    1448 fps - S&W mod 66, 2.5 inch barrel

You’ll notice that the newer S&W 4 inch Mt Gun gave higher velocities than the older 5 inch model 27 S&W and this is because of different internal barrel dynamics of the newer gun.

Due to the long-for-weight all copper bullet, we did not have the case capacity to use a bulky flash retarded powder and thus there is noticeable muzzle flash with this load, except when firing it from the rifle, which yielded little to no flash.

This load is the typical Barn-Burning, Turbo-Charged, Buffalo Bore type of HEAVY 357 mag. load and as such, should only be used in revolvers made of all steel. It should not be fired in light weight alloy framed or cylindered revolvers. Feel free to use it in ALL/ANY 357 mag. chambered rifles and all steel revolvers.

Up for sale is a very collectable and rarer Mosin Nagant PU sniper.

1942 PU sniper production was very low, so any PU dated that year is very difficult to find, this is because PU sniper production didn't start until late in that year and because of it being a transitional year from PE and PEM sniper production .

title: For Sale/Trade:  German Deutsche Werk Ortgies .32ACP W/Ammo, Owner's Manual, Extras
postcontent:
Very good condition German made Ortgies 7.65mm (.32ACP). This gun is the commercial version, and the 6th variant (there were six model variants?). The Ortgies pocket pistols were made (officially) from 1919 to 1924. This particular gun (according to the serial number) was made around 1922-23. The Orgies semi-automatic pistols were excellent, well made guns. The design was ahead of its time. This gun has the factory original 7rd magazine. Overall, this gun is in very good condition. Has all matching numbers (barrel, frame, slide). Bluing is in really good condition for its age (this gun is at least 90 years old). All original finish, not re-blued, or anything like that. Has factory wood grips. The grips has no cracks, splits, or damages. Has a few minor dents and dings. Barrel is in very good condition - has a few minor surface rust. Bore is in very good condition. Has a a few minor rust (the Germans or people back in the old days used highly corrosive ammo). Gun comes with 70 rounds of non-corrosive ammo (50 rounds of FMJ and 20 rounds of hollow points), and a brand new-reproduction firing pin. In addition, there's an old Ortgies owner's manual. It's really worn out, tattered, but all the pages are there (but not intact - it looks like as old as the gun itself). You must be at least 21 years old or older and have a valid Kentucky driver's license (or KY CCDW) to buy/trade this gun. Local (Kentucky) sale/trade only. No shipping. Just email me with any questions. Serious inquiries only please. Thanks for looking.

Gun comes with the following:

- 70 rounds of ammo (50rds of American Eagle FMJ and 20rds of Speer Gold Dot hollow  points) 
- Extra brand new reproduction firing pin (cost me $30)
- factory original owner's manual

-- Extras (ammo and extra firing pin) not pictured but included with the sale/trade --

 * $350 obo, or trade *

 -- Below is an excerpt from one of the Ortgies websites. It is not my own. I am just giving a credit to the author/creator of that particular website. You can do a google (or yahoo) search on this particular pistol on the internet. There are several Ortgies websites on line --

 " The Ortgies pistol has a number of unusual design features. The most obvious is its grip safety which, once squeezed, stays in the “fire” position without further pressure of the hand on the grip. A button on the left side of the gun allows the grip safety to pop back out. Since the grip safety is powered by the striker spring, the safety can only be popped out, i.e., placed in the “safe” position, when the striker is cocked. Hence, if the safety is enabled, the gun is cocked. When the grip safety is enabled, the sear is prevented from moving downward and the tension on the striker spring is reduced. Pressing the safety- enabling button also allows the slide to be lifted off the frame rail for disassembly. The striker serves as the ejector. "
